Here we analyze the University rankings.

H0 : Sample mean for publications for countrieswith top world rank >= population μ for Publications for all countries¶

Ha : Sample mean for publications for countries with top world rank < population μ for Publications for all countries¶

Refer section Hypothesis test after regression models.

From the rankings we can see that India is not in the big league. We believe that for India to be in the big league ie the top numbers, there has to be some factor Indian universities have to work on so that India clinches the top spots.

We propose that publications by faculty is an important factor in world rankings. Our null hypothesis is that publications by faculty is not an important factor in world rankings. Our alternare hypothesis is that publications by faculty is an important factor in world rankings.

Multiple models will be created and one will be selected. It will be applied to a few countries individually for further insights

Multiple models will be created and one will be selected. It will be applied to a few countries individually for further insights

Model 1 Linear regression of world university rankings Regressand world_rank with Regressors : quality_of_education + alumni_employment + quality_of_faculty + publications + influence + citations + patents

import scipy.stats as stats
# get ANOVA table as R like output
import statsmodels.api as sm
from statsmodels.formula.api import ols
import statsmodels.api as sm
from patsy import dmatrices
vars = ['world_rank', 'quality_of_education', 'alumni_employment', 'quality_of_faculty','publications','influence','citations','patents']#, 'Wealth', 'Region']
universityrankings[vars]
#Relation between BMI and other variables - BPMeds + prevalentStroke + currentSmoker + glucose + age
y, X = dmatrices('world_rank  ~ quality_of_education + alumni_employment + quality_of_faculty + publications + influence + citations + patents', data=universityrankings, return_type='dataframe')
mod = sm.OLS(y, X)    # Describe model
res = mod.fit()       # Fit model
print(res.summary())   # Summarize model

Analysis:

  • 91% of world ranking is explained by those variables (drawback : very high numbers of predictors is given here)
  • Omnibus value should be closer to 0. Here it is far away from 0.
  • Probability of Omnibus indicates residuals are not normally distributed
  • Skew is between the range of -2 to +2 but kurtosis is beyond the range of -7 to +7
  • Durbin Watson expeccted is between 1 and 2.
  • Jacque Berra is a confirmation of the Omnibus test. So kurtosis and skew need to be studied
  • Condition Number indicates sensitivity of output to input - should ideally be within 30. Here the values 3.48+03 is 3480 This implies (pending analysis of kurtosis and skew) that the data is very higly dependent on inputs.

y = -52.6402+ 0.0961 quality_of_education + 0.2630 alumni_employment - 0.1890 quality_of_faculty + 0.4223 publications + 0.2857 influence + 0.1494 citations + 0.0886 patents

Here quality_of_faculty drops off from the equation because of the negative coefficient. We will take the variable with the most significant coefficient (publications) for our next analysis. Influence is the next important variable after publications and ideally both publications and influence should be used to identify world rank.

However we will leave out influence for the time being.

91.9% of all variation in world rank can be predicted by publications

The null hypothesis is that the errors are normally distributed. This is accepted and Alternate hypothesis that distribution of errors is not normally distributed is rejected.

Durbin-Watson: 1.385

This is a test of autocorrelation - whether variance in errors is constant. The preferred range is 1-2. This means positive autocorrelation

Prob(JB): 00

Confirms the Prob(Omnibus)

Kurtosis: 7.892

Kurtosis implies data might not be normally distributed.

Skew: -1.142

Data is highly skewed

Cond. No. 3.48e+03

Tests the sensitivity of a function's output to its input. Idea value is within 30. Here the output is highly dependent. Very high multi collinearity.

So as discussed, the ideal approach is to take most important parameter publications and second most influence. But we will proceed only with publications

from patsy import dmatrices

mod = sm.OLS(y, X)    # Describe model
res = mod.fit()       # Fit model
print(res.summary())   # Summarize model

Hypothesis Test¶

H0 : Sample mean for publications for countrieswith top world rank >= population μ for Publications for all countries¶

Ha : Sample mean for publications for countries with top world rank < population μ for Publications for all countries¶

import math  
#calculate population standard deviation for publications
#difference of each number from mean
a = universityrankings['publications']-Mean
#square
b  = a * a
#mean of the squares is the variance
c = b.mean(axis=0)
#stddev is sqrt of variance
= math.sqrt(c)

USA : p score < a - so Null hypothesis rejected. Alternate hypothesis accepted : USA is on top world ranks because Probability of z score of the difference between its mean and Population mean for publications¶

China : p score > a - Null hypothesis can not be rejected.¶

INDIA : p score > a - Null hypothesis can not be rejected.¶

Hence the role of publications viz. hypothesis test and regression¶

Conclusion:

For university rankings, model5 ie predicting world_rank based on publications, influence, citations, alumni_employment seems to be the better model

Rankings in India are not predicted by citations. So Indian universities will need to work more on having more citations so that it can improve university rankings
